    <div class="container">
        <div class="row">
            <div class="col-md-4">
                <div class="feature-box">
                    <h2>User Role:</h2>
                    <p>Normal users or employees typically have limited permissions in the system.</p>
                    <p>Permissions may include:</p>
                    <ul>
                        <li>Viewing their own profile and personal information.</li>
                        <li>Viewing information about other employees or colleagues.</li>
                        <li>Submitting requests or applications (e.g., leave requests, expense claims).</li>
                    </ul>
                    <p>Users are restricted from performing actions such as:</p>
                    <ul>
                        <li>Updating or deleting employee records.</li>
                        <li>Accessing sensitive administrative functionalities.</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>
            </div>
            <div class="col-md-4">
                <div class="feature-box">
                    <h2>Admin Role:</h2>
                    <p>Admins have more advanced permissions compared to regular users.</p>
                    <p>Permissions may include:</p>
                    <ul>
                        <li>Creating, updating, and deleting employee records.</li>
                        <li>Managing department information.</li>
                        <li>Assigning roles and permissions to other users.</li>
                        <li>Generating reports and analytics.</li>
                    </ul>
                    <p>Admins have access to functionalities that facilitate the day-to-day management of employees and organizational data.</p>
                    <p>Admins are restricted from managing other admin and superadmin accounts.</p>

                </div>
            </div>
            <div class="col-md-4">
                <div class="feature-box">
                    <h2>Super Admin Role:</h2>
                    <p>Super admins have the highest level of permissions in the system.</p>
                    <p>In addition to all the permissions granted to admins, super admins have additional privileges, such as:</p>
                    <ul>
                        <li>Managing admin accounts and permissions.</li>
                        <li>Configuring system settings and preferences.</li>
                        <li>Performing system-wide operations like backups, restores, and maintenance tasks.</li>
                    </ul>
                    <p>Super admins have complete control over the system and can perform any action within it, including managing both admin and other superadmin accounts.</p>


                </div>
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>
</div>

